{"/service/ndnp/ak/batch_ak_chinooksalmon_ver03/data/sn84020662/00414185940/1949051601/1257.xml":{"full_text":"Girl Scout News\nThe sixth Girl Scout Law\u2014\u201cA\nGirl Scout is a friend to animals.\u201d\nLet\u2019s take the word \u201cAnimals\u201d\napart and see what they can tell\nyou.\nA stands for\nAn evening of entertainment.\nN stands for\nNew stunts by the bushel\nI stands for\nIdeas\u2014Brand new ones.\nM stands for\nMany speciality numbers\nA stands for\nAction and color.\nL stands for\nLots of fun for all.\nS stands for\nSurprises galore!\nPut them all back together and\nthey spell\u2014the Girl Scout Musical\nRevue and Bazaar! ^he date\u2014Fri\nday evening, the 20th of May The\nplace\u2014the Nome High School au\nditorium The time\u2014eight in the\nevening! Get your tickets today!\nFreighter Tongass\nSold For Scrap\n\nSEATTLE, </P>\u2014The stubby, lit\ntle freighter Tongass, one of the\nbest-known ships in Seattle-Alas\nka trade, has been sold for scrap,\nAlaska Transportation company\ndisclosed Friday.\nSale of the 1,000-gross ton\nwooden freighter to Arthur Men-\n1 delsohn, Seattle scrap dealers was\nconfirmed by S. J. Swanson, vice\ni president and general manager of\nAlaska Transportation company.\nThe ship line suspended opera\ntions last winter, and recently sold\nits passenger ship George Wash\nington the the French Line. Alas\nka Transportation company still\nowns the freighter Empire Conse\nquence.\ni The SS. Tongass has been idle\nsince June, 1947, when she was\nlaid up in Lake Union under re\nstrictions of the Alaska interim\nprogram.\nPIONEER WATER DELIVERY\nSAND and GRAVEL\nGENERAL HAULING\nm\nBOX 17 MAIN 94 or MAIN 70\nI\nr \u2014t\nFrances Wells Virginia M. Peppard\nAnchorage Fairbanks\nArctic Trails\nSHOPPING SERVICE\nWe Buy Anything and Ship Anywhere\nP. O. Box 1156 423 E STREET\nPHONE GREEN 93 ANCHORAGE, ALASKA\n\nEnjoy thi\nwhiskey that's\noa faNamt>*\nKENTUCKY WHISKEY-A BIEND 86 PROOF\nt>< rM\u00bb-Ti ic\u00bb\u00ab orrvrmTT^ rOREQRATION. N. Y. 657i GRAIN NEUTRAL SPIRITS\nSCHOOL NOTES\nSIXTH AND SEVENTH GRADES\nThe sixth and seventh grade\nroom pupils are busy finishing the\nyear\u2019s subjects. The sixth grade i\nhas finished arithmetic, science,\nand history. The seventh grade pu\npils have finished science and are\nbusy taking tests on several\nothers.\nWe are proud of Kay Coulthard\nwho is in the seventh grade in our\nroom and who won Honorable\nMention in the recent Art Contest, i\ndesigning a poster for the Alaska j\nCrippled Children\u2019s Association\nSeal Contest. Our room sent seven\nposters to Anchorage to be judged.!\nAll of them had some excellent1\nwork done on them and these are\npupils are to be commended.\nThe following pupils have been\nneither absent nor tardy for the\nentire school year: Jack Muller.\nDonna Lyle, and Robert Summers.!\nOur room is planning a picnic to\nAnvil Mountain or Hastings!\nCreek, provided we can get there.\nWe hope to go on May 25th or\nMay 26th. We are all looking for\nward to this event and are just as i\nanxious to have our summer\u2019s va-\ncation commence.\nSEVENTH AND EIGHTH GRADE\nEighth grade students are look\ning forward to graduation, and we\nare completing the work in all\nsubjects.\nEighth grade arithmetic class is\nstudying bond, stock, interest and\nmortgage problems; seventh grade,\nbusiness accounts and budgets.\nWe are planning a picnic on the\nlast day of school.\nHIGH SCHOOL\nI\nMinnesota was admitted to the\nUnion on May 11, 1858. The name\nmeans \u201csky-colored water.\u201d There\nare 10,000 lakes and three drain-(\n1 age systems; the Mississippi to the\nsouth, the Red River to the north,\nand Lake Superior to the east. It\nis often called the North Star or\nGopher State. The state flower is\nthe moccasin, and the motto \"The\nStar of the North.\u201d The Chippe\nwas drove out the Sioux Indians\nin the early seventeen hun\ndreds. Half of the population is\nNorwegian, Swedish and Danish.\nTyping I students are finishing\ntheir books.\nEnglish I students are studying\nrhythm in poetry.\nThe sociology students are stu\ndying social control.\nTrigonometry class is applying\nthe oblique triangle formulas to\npractical problems.\nGeometry students are making\ni\nfair booklets and studying a unit:\non trigonometry.\nStudents in the blue print read-;\ning class are making blue prints.\nIn physical education, the bad\nminton tournament is still holding\nthe students\u2019 interests.\nThe Junior-Senior Banquet will j\ni be on Wednesday evening, May 18, j\nj while the Prom is scheduled for\nSaturday evening, May 21st.\nThe musical recital last Thurs\nday evening given by the Girls\nGlee Club under the direction of\nMrs. W. Cameron, was a great j\nsuccess. The harmony of voices j\nwas excellent, while the musical\ntalent of some students was almost\nastounding.\nLight travels 186.300 miles per\nsecond. It takes light 150 years to\ntravel from the star Arcturus to\nthe earth. In other words, the light\nthat we see from Artcurus is the\nlight sent out in 1789 when Ceorge\nWashington was President. It\ntakes 47 years for light to reach us\nfrom Polaris our North Star. The I\nlight we see these evenings from\nPolaris left in 1902 or when Nome\nwas first being built into a city I\nand the gold rush was still on.\nA. POLET RETURNS FROM\nBUSINESS TOUR OF ALASKA\nAntonio Polet, Nome\u2019s leading\narts and crafts dealer returned\nyesterday after having made a\ncareful survey of the development\nof native crafts in the Territory.\nHe personally visited many of the\ndealers in various Alaskan cities\nas well as contacting and inter\nviewing government officials in\nJuneau as to plans to handle the\nindustry.\nOne of the necessary moves de\ncided upon, he states, is the organ\nization of arts and crafts dealers\ninto an association. He states that\nto date over thirty dealers agreed\nto organize and attend a meeting\nto be called next winter.\nWherever he visited he found\nhimself called upon to speak with\nchambers of commerce, Rotarians,\nLions Clubs, etc., to explain the\nachievement and aspirations of i\nthe Alaska Development Board, of\nwhich he is a member, and found\nthat the widely-varied activities\nof the board have not been under\nstood. He stated that he plans to\nsubmit to the board the problem\nof industrial development and\ntourist economy as well as the vi\ntal inter-Alaska transportati o n\nproblem.\nHe stated that Alaska is no long\ner a child but has reached adult\nage and must stand on its own feet\nand profit from its wealth and po-\ntentialities. He does not believe1\nfrom what he has seen that there\nwill be a business recession and\nthat the future of Alaska is as\nsured, but it must be united and\ndeveloped on sane and construe- i\ntive lines.\n\nThe Walrus Club held its second\nsuccessful dance at the Nevada\nLounge on Saturday evening with\nthe hall filled to capacity with\ndancers enjoying the music of an\norchestra from Marks Field.\nFISH AND WILDLIFE TO TEST\nFISHERIES NEAR NOME\nAn announcement has been re\nceived from the Fish and Wildbit\nService that they are planning t<\ninvestigate commercial fishery\npossibilities in Kotzebue and Nor\nton Sound this summer. This in\nvestigation is in accordance with\nthe budget proposal submitted by\nthe* Alaska Fisheries Experiment; '1\nCommission and it is stated that\ntheir work will not duplicate the\nwork of the Fish and Wildlitt\nService research vessels which art\nto conduct exploratory fishing oj\nerations.\nThe bulk of the investigation\nwill be handled by Norman Wigu\ntoff and Clarence Carlson, fishery\nmarketing specialists and technol\nogists who will visit in Nome\nsometime between June 15 and\nAugust 1st.\nH. W. Magnusson, chemist m\ncharge of the commission will ar\nrive on the Wednesday flight of\nthe Pan American after a confer\nence in Fairbanks with ^the Uni\nversity of Alaska. He will visit in\nNome, Kotzebue and Teller.\nAlbin Moe, brother of Mrs. EarJ\nCoulthard, arrived yesterday for a\nvisit with the Coulthard family\nbefore leaving for the Kougarok\nwhere he will work with the Sil\nver Bow Mining Co., for the sum\nmer. Mr. Moe comes from Issa\nquah, Wash.\nRoy Earling, vice president and\ngeneral manager for Alaskan op\nerations for the U. S. Smelting Co.\narrived yesterday for a confer\nence with department heads here\nin connection with this summer\u2019s\noprations. The company is plan\nning to operate two dredges this\nseason.\nThe Phoenicians invented glas;\nr\nA--\\\nWE CARRY LARGE ASSORTMENT OF\nFINE LIQUORS, BEER AND WINE\nOut-of-Town Orders Carefully Handled\nTHE NOME LIQUOR STORE\nSERVICE CLEANERS\n4th and B Streets\u2014Opposite School House\nQUALITY DRY CLEANING A SPECIALTY\nMr. and Mrs. Carl Mickleson, Props.\nPrompt and Courteous Service\nPhone RED 96\nTHE GLUE POT SODA FOUNTAIN\nServes the BEST ICE CREAM\nMADE DAILY\nAT THE GLUE POT\nWe Carry Also Standard Brands of\nCigars, Cigarettes, Tobacco, Candy\n-\u2022FRESH POPCORN\nTHE gTuE POT","height":"27328","width":"20112"}}
